{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17655112","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17655112"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:59:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:59:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18651"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18651","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18651"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.03,0.35,0.6,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11383"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114974"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11383","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11383"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18651"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96980"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6673"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26396"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26697"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27176"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114974","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114974"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe internal carotid artery terminates by dividing into multiple branches that provide vascular supply to different regions of the cerebrum. One particular branch has primary responsibility for perfusing the medial aspect of the cerebral hemisphere.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which artery is the main supplier to this medial cerebral region?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Posterior cerebral","Superior cerebellar","Middle cerebral","Anterior cerebral","Posterior communicating"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe cerebral circulation involves several major arteries that supply distinct territories of the brain. The medial surface of the cerebral hemisphere receives its primary blood supply from a specific branch of the internal carotid system.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior cerebral artery\u003C/strong\u003E serves as the principal vascular supply to the medial aspects of the cerebral hemisphere, delivering blood to medial regions of both frontal and parietal lobes, including cortical areas controlling lower extremity motor and sensory functions. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior cerebral artery\u003C/strong\u003E has a different distribution, primarily perfusing the occipital cortex and inferior aspects of the temporal lobe. The \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperior cerebellar artery\u003C/strong\u003E belongs to the posterior circulation and provides blood flow to the upper cerebellar surfaces rather than cerebral tissue. The \u003Cstrong\u003Emiddle cerebral artery\u003C/strong\u003E has responsibility for the lateral cerebral surface and deep structures but does not supply medial cortical areas. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior communicating artery\u003C/strong\u003E functions as an anastomotic vessel within the circle of Willis, linking the internal carotid system to the posterior cerebral artery rather than directly supplying brain parenchyma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The anterior cerebral artery supplies the medial surface of the cerebral hemisphere from frontal to parietal lobes.","The anterior cerebral artery is a terminal branch of the internal carotid artery.","The anterior cerebral arteries of both sides are connected by the anterior communicating artery."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach 